Problem statement (Term Deposit Sale)¶

**Goal**

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

**Resources Available** The historical data for this project is available in file
https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing

Attribute information

**Input variables:**

Bank client data:

    1. age: Continuous feature
    1. job: Type of job (management, technician, entrepreneur, blue-collar, etc.)
    1. marital: marital status (married, single, divorced)
    1. education: education level (primary, secondary, tertiary)
    1. default: has credit in default?
    1. housing: has housing loan?
    1. loan: has personal loan?
    1. balance in account

Related to previous contact:

    1. contact: contact communication type
    1. month: last contact month of year
    1. day: last contact day of the month
    1. duration: last contact duration, in seconds*

Other attributes:

    1. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client
    1. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (-1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days)
    1. previous: number of times the client has been contacted before for the last campaign to subscribe term deposit
    1. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign

Output variable (desired target):

    1. Target: Tell us has the client subscribed a term deposit. (Yes, No)

  • education: higher education leads to higher balance and more conversion rate to open accounts.

Prepare the data for analytics¶

Data model is ready for further process
As part of Univariate and Bivariate analysis we have already done pre processing cover above in "PreProcessingTag#":

  • Converted all object columns to categorical set (PreProcessingTag0)
  • Dropped four columns  -- (PreProcessingTag1): 'campaign', 'pdays','previous' and 'poutcome' data is skewed and 81%+ in all four column does not have relevant info. Also correlation is not significant to the 'Target' column. Dropping these four coulmns  

  • Imputation:        -- PreProcessingTag2: 'education' is unknown, values are very less as compared to huge dataset , but also significant rows(1800+) cannot be dropped . Imputing unknows by merging unknown (-1) to second least catagoric primary (1)'contact' is unknown values is second highest need to be imputed with median        -- PreProcessingTag3: 'contact' is unknown values is second highest need to be imputed with median  and 'job' is unknown values is least in all category , need to be imputed with medain

  • Attribute types were correct in the initial stage by converting all object data types to Category.

## Define X and Y variables

#Create function to plot ROC plot for given logistic regression (logreg) , dependent test data (y_data) 
# and independent data (x_data)
#AUC ROC curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve

def draw_roc(pLogreg,pX_data,pY_data):
    logit_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(pY_data, pLogreg.predict(pX_data))
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(pY_data, pLogreg.predict_proba(pX_data)[:,1])
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='Logistic Regression (area = %0.2f)' % logit_roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.savefig('Log_ROC')
    plt.show()

from yellowbrick.classifier import ClassificationReport, ROCAUC
# Creating a function for visualizing classifier results
def visClassifierResults(model_w_parameters):
    viz = ClassificationReport(model_w_parameters)
    viz.fit(X_train, y_train)
    viz.score(X_test, y_test)
    viz.show()

    roc = ROCAUC(model_w_parameters)
    roc.fit(X_train, y_train)
    roc.score(X_test, y_test)
    roc.show()

Conclusion :¶

  • Most models are in similar range for given dataset
  • But for this dataset, Random forest and Gradient Boost models give the best results on test predictions(where estimator for boosting and bagging are set to 200)
  • With lower value for estimator (50), for this dataset, Random forest and Bagging models give the best results on test predictions

Why Random forest model best?¶

Random forest modelling has best accuracy figures but does have better precision , F1 and recall as compared to any other model . The AOC graph does show better coverage. And it does predict better with smaller estimator size making is more efficient in terms of resource consumptions
